"Imagine a future where hackers take down power grids across the country, disable air traffic control and cause trains to crash into each other. They delete all data held by the major banks, release chlorine gas from chemical plants, trigger explosions at oil refineries and take out the military's classified and unclassified networks. Thousands of people die even before anarchy takes hold in the wake of ATM machines shutting down, cities running out of food and looters taking to the streets. While such colourful images of the potential ramifications of a cyber-attack on critical national infrastructure may make a good story, the big question is just how valid are they? And who is – or should be – responsible for securing critical national infrastructure? Cath Everett looks at how safe such infrastructure is today, where the holes are and whether existing governance models are enough."
